<body>
<segment id="1" parent="1001" relname="preparation">Choose a Fund Manager</segment>
<segment id="2" parent="1002" relname="span">By choosing the right fund</segment>
<segment id="3" parent="1003" relname="joint">to invest your money in ,</segment>
<segment id="4" parent="1004" relname="span">you can have a team of professionals picking stocks ,</segment>
<segment id="5" parent="1005" relname="joint">managing your money</segment>
<segment id="6" parent="1005" relname="joint">and executing trades .</segment>
<segment id="7" parent="1008" relname="span">Large funds can afford to have a separate person</segment>
<segment id="8" parent="7" relname="elaboration">focusing on picking stocks ,</segment>
<segment id="9" parent="1010" relname="span">allocating the assets of the fund into different areas</segment>
<segment id="10" parent="9" relname="elaboration">( stocks , bonds , cash , etc )</segment>
<segment id="11" parent="1009" relname="same_unit">and managing the most efficient tax position .</segment>
<segment id="12" parent="1012" relname="span">Large funds may also re-invest some of their money into other funds</segment>
<segment id="13" parent="12" relname="elaboration">in the pursuit of lower risk and higher gains .</segment>
<segment id="14" parent="1014" relname="preparation">The great thing about mutual funds is that you share the cost of these services with thousands of other investors in the same fund .</segment>
<segment id="15" parent="1015" relname="preparation">Steps</segment>
<segment id="16" parent="1016" relname="sequence">Research the fund manager &apos;s track record .</segment>
<segment id="17" parent="1016" relname="sequence">Not every fund performs well .</segment>
<segment id="18" parent="19" relname="condition">Just because a fund has performed well in the past</segment>
<segment id="19" parent="1019" relname="span">does n’t necessarily tell you how the fund will perform in the future .</segment>
<segment id="20" parent="1022" relname="circumstance">In picking a fund ,</segment>
<segment id="21" parent="1022" relname="span">it helps to research the fund ’s key personnel , their experience and accomplishments , the fees</segment>
<segment id="22" parent="21" relname="elaboration">they charge , and their investment style .</segment>
<segment id="23" parent="1024" relname="span">Managing other people ’s money</segment>
<segment id="24" parent="23" relname="elaboration">requires experience , maturity and a strong sense of responsibility .</segment>
<segment id="25" parent="1016" relname="sequence">Check a fund manager ’s track record .</segment>
<segment id="26" parent="1028" relname="span">How well did they do at the last fund</segment>
<segment id="27" parent="26" relname="elaboration">they managed ?</segment>
<segment id="28" parent="1030" relname="concession">While veteran managers ca n&apos;t guarantee better performance than a fresh face ,</segment>
<segment id="29" parent="1030" relname="span">there is a lot</segment>
<segment id="30" parent="29" relname="purpose">to be said for experience in the markets .</segment>
<segment id="31" parent="1032" relname="span">Having a long view of your manager ’s history</segment>
<segment id="32" parent="1034" relname="attribution">will help you to see</segment>
<segment id="33" parent="1035" relname="span">how they performed in both bull</segment>
<segment id="34" parent="1036" relname="span">( strong ) and bear</segment>
<segment id="35" parent="34" relname="restatement">( weak )</segment>
<segment id="36" parent="1034" relname="same_unit">markets .</segment>
<segment id="37" parent="1038" relname="same_unit">A consistent performer in both good and bad times</segment>
<segment id="38" parent="1038" relname="same_unit">is more likely to bring you peace of mind with your investments .</segment>
<segment id="39" parent="1040" relname="question">How does a manager &apos;s track record compare to that of his/her peers ?</segment>
<segment id="40" parent="1040" relname="sequence">Be careful with comparisons .</segment>
<segment id="41" parent="1040" relname="sequence">Different managers employ different investing styles .</segment>
<segment id="42" parent="1040" relname="sequence">Some choose growth stocks ,</segment>
<segment id="43" parent="1044" relname="span">ones they expect to grow in value</segment>
<segment id="44" parent="43" relname="manner">without paying much in dividends .</segment>
<segment id="45" parent="1040" relname="sequence">Others may look for income from dividends .</segment>
<segment id="46" parent="1047" relname="span">Still others may choose stocks</segment>
<segment id="47" parent="48" relname="attribution">they believe</segment>
<segment id="48" parent="1048" relname="span">the market has undervalued .</segment>
<segment id="49" parent="1051" relname="preparation">Add “ Alpha ” :</segment>
<segment id="50" parent="1051" relname="same_unit">An important measure of a fund manager ’s value</segment>
<segment id="51" parent="1052" relname="span">is the “ alpha ”</segment>
<segment id="52" parent="1053" relname="joint">that they can add .</segment>
<segment id="53" parent="1054" relname="span">“ Alpha ” is the measure of how much more the manager adds to the value of your investment</segment>
<segment id="54" parent="53" relname="antithesis">than if you had simply invested in an index fund .</segment>
<segment id="55" parent="1056" relname="span">An index fund attempts to mirror the market</segment>
<segment id="56" parent="1057" relname="span">by investing in every company</segment>
<segment id="57" parent="1058" relname="span">( or a representative sampling of companies )</segment>
<segment id="58" parent="57" relname="elaboration">listed in a particular index .</segment>
<segment id="59" parent="1060" relname="span">Such a list may reflect a particular industry , economic sector , geographic region , company size , or investing style .</segment>
<segment id="60" parent="1061" relname="span">You can discover a fund &apos;s &quot; alpha &quot; measurement</segment>
<segment id="61" parent="60" relname="means">by researching the fund online at Morningstar.com or various other fund-analysis services .</segment>
<segment id="62" parent="1040" relname="sequence">Compare with index funds .</segment>
<segment id="63" parent="1064" relname="span">Generally index funds charge lower fees ,</segment>
<segment id="64" parent="63" relname="cause">because they face lower research-and-analysis expenses .</segment>
<segment id="65" parent="1040" relname="sequence">They may be expected to do as well as the relevant market in general .</segment>
<segment id="66" parent="1066" relname="span">If , on the other hand , you choose to pay the higher fees</segment>
<segment id="67" parent="68" relname="condition">associated with a managed fund ,</segment>
<segment id="68" parent="1067" relname="span">be sure that the fund manager is not merely following some index .</segment>
<segment id="69" parent="1069" relname="preparation">Video</segment>
<segment id="70" parent="1070" relname="preparation">Tips</segment>
<segment id="71" parent="1070" relname="joint">In regulated financial markets like Europe , UK and Australia , governing bodies publish regular performance figures of the various funds on offer .</segment>
<segment id="72" parent="1072" relname="span">These bodies will have information about the key personnel</segment>
<segment id="73" parent="1073" relname="joint">running a fund</segment>
<segment id="74" parent="1073" relname="joint">and may also attempt to define their specific styles .</segment>
<segment id="75" parent="1071" relname="span">In the United States there are a number of online sources of such information , notably Morningstar .</segment>
